title: What Nobody Tells You About 90s UKG Drums (Riordan / Josh Baker Bounce)

transcript.text: I'm gonna teach you guys how to shake that butt like Riordan. Now a lot of the times I'm building my grooves out with the 909 core kit. It takes the choice out of everything because a lot of people get stuck picking the samples. It's very important to work on the rhythm, the midi first. So let's get this thing started. So here we have an 8 bar loop and all I'm going to do is put the open hat on the off. So I'm going to go into the 909 open hat and lower it. From there the clap on the 2 and the 4. Now here's where we're going to swag it up. We're going to right click and now we're going to go into six scenes. Now these new two sections here is where the swing of a track in most house tracks is going to come from. So in theory if you wanted something set in stone that you can always do. It's not wrong to say that if you're making a track like this you can always have a snare drum hit. When the clap hits 3 squares to the right in 16th grid. Now I'm going to switch this because that sounds like someone's getting their ass beat. I can use these features here to design the drum. Usually I like to lower down the tone to make it a lot more tight. Now from there I can choose to do another one but I'm going to follow the man reordering himself. I'm going to do another one here but this time I'm not going to double. I can duplicate this and here I'm going to do a triple hit. Now with these ones there's something very important that you must do and that is control the velocity. The velocity is a parameter which is going to be able to know how hard the note is being hit or how loud you want the snare to be played at the exact moment that we're altering the  So what I can do is on some parts lower the velocity like so. It's going to make it like hit like loud. But the thing that I've noticed with people is that when you play something a lot quieter the tonality kind of feels like it's changing. But in theory it's not. It's just the volume is going down. What makes people hear that and go is there pitch automation going on which sometimes there might be however just going down the volume you can add a lot of like that feeling of groove. It's not robotic because everything's hitting at the same velocity the same volume. And I'm just going to duplicate this across like so. And yeah you can add more variation more micro variations if you want but with this you're going to be pretty much better than most. Now this whole time I thought I didn't have swing but I do have swing which you can find here. Now this is what's really going to make the space of loop that you've created just feel a lot more alive. And what this is going to do is it's going to grab these notes and it's going to shift them to the right slightly. Now by how much is dependent on the groove the swing you decide to apply. So if we click here on the bring up your collection of grooves so I'm going to have different ones than you. Everyone's going to have all different kinds you know variety. There we go but the one I've decided to pick is the Ableton one which is the swing 1664. 64 is the intensity of the swing and the 16 means that it's going to be applied to the notes that are hitting on those 16's those pockets we were talking about. Notice that when I have the timing up you want to bob the head but when I have it down it sounds bleached. We need to unbleach that. I added a tambourine which is also going to get the swing. If you were going to be applying swing to a loop you command A the loop by clicking here and then you command U or quantize and you can also go into Ableton's transform section here and quantize it here as you can see there there's a quantize feature and then from there you would quantize to 16. Now from there what Ableton's going to do since you're telling it that you want the swing 16 on it which you're going to be able to see here. From there it's going to apply the same swing we've added to this snare here. So if I were to commit it by just clicking this arrow you're going to see that some notes are getting shifted to the right while other ones remain and that is what's going to give you that swag. But what if you wanted to program your own tambourine and you don't want to use mine's for some reason. Just get yourself a nice tambourine sample set at 16 like so. Now I'm going to loop it so that I can drag it out so it's already looped I'm just going to drag it all the way because the sample's not really going to change so that's where we loop it. Now from here you can choose to move some of the notes or play with the velocities. You can also get a more natural sounding one. I'm going to show you guys a super clutch trick that's super easy to implement. One thing you can do is you can grab this guy and from there command E and turn it into 2. So now you get this double hit there which is going to add even more swag. And since you have this swing applied this open hat gets that swing the last one and that makes a tasty ass boom. What magic. Right. And then you can play with the velocity too if you choose. I do have a reverse clap here. It's been making itself known. I'm just going to lower the volume. The purpose of it is to lead you into that last clap which creates a very nice swag and another variation to it of course is to do it every 2 bars if you choose to. From there I recommend grabbing loops and chopping up the parts that you like. For example. There's a very heavy loop that has a lot going on. However, I don't really want all of that so what I can do is start to chop to get what I like. Cue it to just grab that rim that I really like the pattern. It's a very dusty loop. Now the reason that I'm adding loops like this is because I'm trying to fill in the gaps with other style of drums to add flavor but at the same time sometimes we might want more we just don't know and that's where sample packs will come into play. You should use them as sort of inspiration where you could maybe get inspired and do your own pattern to it or maybe you like the tone and texture that the sample provides. Back then I was super super strict on not using top loops like this over existing drums because there's always the fear or the risk of cancelling out phasing out which is where two drums that sound the same hit and it sounds rather odd. However, after being in some sessions with some more veteran producers that make some bomb music I've noticed a lot of them don't really care about it and when I asked the way it was explained to me is that a lot of the times these drums will add a noise floor and what that means is without those drums there's like an empty gap in the song that isn't being filled and the way they see it it adds texture. The key thing of course is being aware that this can lead to some detrimental issues that will arise with the audio where you're going to find like the audio just sounds a lot shittier but the question is is it on purpose and does it add to the character of the song and that's really up to you to decide what your taste as a producer. And of course I'm making it a case to use the 909 kick drum from Ableton it's just it's like a like a test to yourself when you get that thing to sound good then you know you're a real producer. But from here I'm using standard clip just to clip off just the tip the key thing though is I don't want to clip the low end because anytime you clip low and it's going to sound so I'm going to ease off and there we go. That's just controlling that peak because that peak is going to trigger the compressor so this is just a couple of things that I've done in order to make this be a lot more friendlier to compressors and the limiter on the master. Let me show you when I turn all this off how it sounds. Yeah so these drums need a bit of love let me show you what's really going to give these drums flavor this is the stuff they don't show you because they just don't want you to have the flavor they're scared of your ideas because they know you are going to kill it more than they are. Let's not blow someone else's candle to light ours unless they ain't gonna show us the goods. The first thing is some compression this is something that you can write down for yourself that you can always have and that is going to be a compressor the glue from Ableton that is going to be set to a two to one ratio two for every two db that goes over the threshold being hit when the needle moves one db will come out so it's not going to be that hard. The next thing is the attack can either be 30 or 10 it just really depends on how tight you want your drums to feel 10 is going to allow for more gain reduction and it's going to grab onto the drum a lot quicker meaning that it's going to be a lot shorter on the compression 30 you're again it's going to be very minuscule because we're talking about 10 milliseconds 30 milliseconds here so i'm going to go with the 10 release we want it fast because if we leave it that needle takes forever to go down and with drums they're fast hitting right so we want this compressor to grab on and do its thing when needed. Now the way this thing glues is by controlling the volume if something goes above the threshold meaning the clap hits a little louder than everything else because it's activating the threshold and nothing else is then it's going reduce the volume at that instant when the clap hits or 10 milliseconds after it triggers it meaning the volume gets reduced on the clap making it feel a lot more glued because the volume isn't like there's not a lot of change in volume inside the drum. Tape saturation is one of those things that's very beautiful essentially mimicking the idea of recording something to tape and as something was recorded to tape there was some saturation that occurred probably during like someone running hot on it and this one i like to use the drum bus preset and then from there i'll play with the input and the output so for example i'm going to lower these down right now so we don't bust that is how like it sounds louder yet it's quieter.
